spaces.description:
Product of {S000038} and {S000103}. Used in
{{mathse:3145712}} to construct a {P000130}, {P000003}, and {P000036}
but not {P000013} space.

$X$ is the subspace of the product $\prod_{n\in\omega}(\omega_{n+1}+1)$ with the box topology consisting of all $f\in \prod_{n\in \omega}(\omega_{n+1}+1)$ such that $\omega< \text{cf}(f(n))$ for all $n$ (see {{wikipedia:Cofinality#Cofinality_of_ordinals_and_other_well-ordered_sets}}).

Defined (as the space called $X'$) and shown to be the Hewitt realcompactification of {S138} in section IV.4 of {{zb:0224.54019}} 
(see remark 8.8 of {{doi:10.1007/978-1-4615-7819-2}} for the definition of Hewitt realcompactification).

theorems.description:
If $X$ is $T_3$, it is $T_2$.  So given distinct points $a,b\in X$, there are disjoint open $O_a$ and $O_b$ containing $a$ and $b$ respectively. Then $a \notin \operatorname{cl}(O_b)$ and by regularity there is an open $U$ containing $a$ with $\operatorname{cl}(U) \cap \operatorname{cl}(O_b) = \emptyset$.

Asserted in Figure 1 of {{zb:0386.54001}}
(where T_3 means regular).

If $f:X \rightarrow [0,1]$ is a continuous function with $f(a)=0$ and $f(B)=\{1\}$, then $f^{-1}([0,\frac{1}{3}))$ and $f^{-1}((\frac{2}{3},1])$ are disjoint open sets with disjoint closures containing $a$ and $B$ respectively.

Asserted in Figure 1 of {{zb:0386.54001}}
(where T_3 means regular and T_{3.5} means completely regular).

As defined on page 223 of {{zb:0386.54001}}
all continuous functions from a hyperconnected space to the
reals are constant.

As defined on page 223 of {{zb:0386.54001}}
all continuous functions from a strongly connected space to the
reals are constant and thus have compact images.

Follows from the definition on page 31 of {{zb:0386.54001}}
as the path connecting two distinct points would yield a nonsingleton path
component.

By the main theorem of the article {{doi:10.1090/S0002-9939-1973-0322812-9}},
if $X$ is {P7}, embeds as a closed subspace of a product of {P194} spaces (e.g. it is itself {P194}),
and every closed discrete subspace of $X$ is {P164} (e.g. it is itself {P164}), then $X$ is {P162}.

A separable metrizable space embeds into {S30}
(see Theorem 23.1 in {{zb:1052.54001}}), which is a W-group since
(1) {S30|P87},
(2) {S30|P28}
and (3) {T473}.

The $\Sigma$-product

$\quad Y=\{x=(x_\alpha)\in\mathbb R^\Gamma:\{\alpha:x_\alpha\ne 0\}\text{ is countable}\}$

for some set $\Gamma$ is a subgroup of the topological group $(\mathbb R^\Gamma,+)$
with the product topology, and is {P187}
since {S25|P187}
and the {P187} property is preserved by $\Sigma$-products.

Assuming $X$ is nonempty, let $x$ be a point of $X$.  By {P24},
$x$ has an open neighborhood $V$ with compact closure.  But in a {P39}
space every nonempty open set is dense.  So $X=\overline V$ is compact.

See Theorem 2.3 in {{zb:0555.54015}}.

The proof shows that if $X$ satisfies the hypotheses, it is {P110}.
The rest follows by results known to pi-base:
{P133} spaces are {P88}
[(Explore)](https://topology.pi-base.org/spaces?q=LOTS%2B%7ECollectionwise+normal)
and {P1};
hence $X$ is {P53}
[(Explore)](https://topology.pi-base.org/spaces?q=Collectionwise+normal%2BDevelopable%2B%24T_0%24%2B%7EMetrizable).

This is Corollary 3 of {{zb:0164.53101}}
([ResearchGate](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/248119266_Total_paracompactness_and_paracompact_dispersed_spaces)),
where "paracompact" assumes {P3}
and "dispersed" means {P51}.

Established as Corollary 2.2 of Theorem 2.1 in {{zb:1126.54010}}
(available [here](https://topology.nipissingu.ca/tp/reprints/v29/tp29201.pdf)).
Note that the proof of Theorem 2.1 contains errors which need corrections. These are discussed in {{mo:506776}}.

traits.description:
$X$ is the product of two spaces which admits a topological group structure:
{S2|P87}
and {S194|P87}.

{S43} admits a compactification homeomorphic to {S93}
and is not a $G_\delta$ subset therein.
See {{mathse:5011073}}.

Every neighbourhood of an irrational number contains an interval.
An open interval in $X$ is homeomorphic to $X$ and hence not {P121}
(e.g. {S58|P10}).

The map $f:X\to X$ defined by
$$f(x)=
\begin{cases}
1^* &\text{if }x = 1,\\
1 &\text{if }x = 1^*,\\
(1 + x)/2 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$
is continuous with no fixed point.

$X$ is covered by the countably many subspaces
$[0,\omega_1]\times\{n\}$ for $n<\omega$ and $[0,\omega_1)\times\{\omega\}$,
with each of them {P198}
since {S36|P198}
and {S35|P198}.

The clopen subspace $q(\{0\}\times[0,\omega]\times\{0,1\})$ is homeomorphic
to {S20}
and {S20|P85}.

$X$ is the union of two singletons and
countably many spaces homeomorphic to {S79}
and {S79|P198}.

For each point either the row is clopen and homeomorphic to {S154}
or the column is clopen and homeomorphic to {S20}.
{S154|P16} and {S20|P16}.

The space contains an open subspace homeomorphic
to {S154}
and {S154|P120}.

$X$ is a subspace of the product of {S20}
and {S154}.
{S20|P186}
and {S154|P186}.

{S30} has a coarser topology than $X$.
{S30|P26}
and {S30|P53}.

The complement of the $x$-axis is homeomorphic to {S176}
and {S176|P64}.
So $X$ is {P64} since it contains a dense subspace that is {P64}.

The result follows from {S3|P87}
and {S27|P87},
and the fact that a product of topological groups is a topological group.

The collection 
$\{((\omega\setminus \{n\})\times\omega)\cup\{\infty_x\}:n<\omega\}
\cup
\{(\omega\times(\omega\setminus \{0\}))\cup\{\infty_y\}:n<\omega\}
\cup
\{\{(n,m)\}:n,m<\omega\}$ is a basis of regular open sets.

The closed subspace $\{0\}\times (\omega_1 + 1)\subseteq X$
is homeomorphic to {S155}
and {S155|P23}.

Every nonempty set $A\subseteq X$ has a minimum element $\alpha$ by well-orderedness.
As a subspace, $A$ is {P202} with $\alpha$ as a focal point;
hence $A$ is {P16}.

{S101}
can be embedded as a subspace of {S1103}
and {S101|P191}.
